I found these snippets:
<details>
<summary>https://psalm.dev/r/ad022887b0</summary>

```php
<?php

/**
 * @psalm-assert-if-false non-empty-string $string
 *
 * @psalm-pure
 */
function is_empty(?string $string): bool
{
    return null === $string || '' === $string;
}


/**
 * @return null|non-empty-string
 */
function to_non_empty_string(mixed $value): ?string
{
    if (is_string($value) && '' !== $value) {
        return $value;
    }

    if (is_int($value)) {
        $v = (string) $value;
        /** @psalm-trace $v */
        if (!is_empty($v)) {
            /** @psalm-trace $v */
            return $v;
        }
    }

    return null;
}
```

```
Psalm output (using commit 25659dd):

INFO: Trace - 28:13 - $v: numeric-string

INFO: Trace - 26:9 - $v: numeric-string

INFO: MoreSpecificReturnType - 15:12 - The declared return type 'non-empty-string|null' for to_non_empty_string is more specific than the inferred return type 'null|string'
```
</details>

> It is: https://3v4l.org/pF4sm

> non-empty-string does not mean that the string is literally empty. It means calling empty() on it will return false.

I don't think that's the case in psalm, as the following is okay:

```

/**
 * @return null|non-empty-string
 */
function to_non_empty_string(mixed $value): ?string
{
    if (is_string($value) && '' !== $value) {
        return $value;
    }

    return null;
}
```

if `"0"` is considered empty in psalm, then the above code *shall not pass* as we might be returning `"0"`.

